<font color="#FF0000">REPLY TO BACSI BEFORE 8 PM</font><br>
<tt>Mon Nov 17 22:56:30 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Bacsi - Your posts are a thing of beauty and enlightenment, and COURAGE. Even I would not go back and want to read what I posted a year ago.  I believe I have learned alot since. When we started I thought all v.n.vets were freeway bums with cardboard &quot;will work for food-god bless&quot; signs, and lived under the overpasses.  With the exception of one or two, (I guess they have laptops and satalitte uplinks), I really came to understand, and have many e mail pals now.<br><br>
I am not an M.D. (god forbid). When I was doing my two years of &quot;valuable&quot; service to my country (per definition of my draft board) I was a poly sci grad.  During the second year of my service, I got involved in free clinic counseling, and found I was good at it. Talking down bad trips, etc.  In 71, when I was &quot;free&quot;, I toured Canada for the hell of it, and then went back to college, got a B.S. in Psych, then a M.A. in 1974, and on to becoming a psychologist.  <br><br>
In California, there are many types of therapist licenses and a ongoing 30 year turf battle over who can do what to whom. I am licensed at the M.A. level as a Marriage, Family, and Child Counselor, althought I went on to get a Ph.D in the early 80's. To upgrade the license requires I do a free year undersupervision (3000) hours, which is absurd, so there are about 9000 of us with MFCC licenses and PH.D degrees.  A &quot;true&quot; Licensed Clinical Psychologist in CALIF is one who has a PHD and the PHD License. There is no difference in what we do, from testing to psychotherapy, just the use of the word &quot;clinical psychologist&quot;. Stupid is as Stupid does.<br><br>
If you went back and reread the archives, look for the posts from DocDel. A combat medic. I believe he is the bravest man I ever talked to, and feel very special to call him my friend.  As for C.O.-Medics, God, they freak me out. If I had to be in the jungle of Nam, the last thing I would have wanted was a Red Cross on my helmet. I would have wanted all the firepower I could carry, and maybe a tank or two.<br><br>
This site has been very tough for me, from being abrasive to confronting me on my thinking, to getting me to acknowledge vets, and even to getting me to go to the wall.  As such I treasure it. I get way too emotional at times and flame, I agree. Like the advent of e mail. You can't go out to the mail box in the AM and remove the letter you wrote the night before, perhaps after one Jack D too many. I am clearly quilty of that.  I have made myself a promise to never SEND after 8 PM, so I must sign off now. It is 7:57. Look foward to more between us.  I am still blown away by your Kent State and CSN&amp;Y analogy. It is classic.  My compliments to you.<br><br>

<p><code>-- on file  (Barry C. Spatz aka doc spatz) </code><p>


